description: Deep region-based object detector consists of a region proposal step and a deep object recognition step. In this work, we make significant improvements on both of the two steps. For region proposal we propose a novel lightweight cascade structure which can effectively improve RPN proposal quality. For object recognition we re-implement global context modeling with a few modifications and obtain a performance boost. Besides, we apply the idea of pre-training extensively and show its importance in both steps. Together with common training and testing tricks, we improve Faster R-CNN baseline by a large margin. This submission reports single model results.

description: Our entry is based on Deformable Convolutional Networks [1] and R-FCN [2]. Deformable Convolutional Networks introduce two new modules to enhance the transformation modeling capacity of CNNs, namely, deformable convolution and deformable RoI pooling. By replacing their plain counterparts in R-FCN, it gives significant improvement for R-FCN. Our model is based on Aligned Inception-ResNet [1, 3] pre-trained on the 1000-class ImageNet classification training set and fine-tuned on the MS COCO trainval set. OHEM is used during training. Multi-scale test and iterative bounding box average are applied during inference. description: We train neural networks with depth of over 150 layers for classification, detection, and segmentation. We propose a “deep residual learning” framework [a] that eases the optimization and convergence of extremely deep networks. Our “deep residual nets” enjoy accuracy gains when the networks are substantially deeper than those used previously. Such accuracy gains are not witnessed for many common networks when going deeper. Our instance semantic system is based on our work in [b]. We build a Multi-task Network Cascade for proposing regions, regressing masks, and categorizing instances. We develop an end-to-end algorithm for training this causal, cascaded system. In particular, we propose an “RoI warping” layer that is differentiable with respect to the region coordinates, so the entire backpropagation can be performed in a theoretically valid way. Our object detection system is based on the “Faster R-CNN” system in our NIPS paper [c]. The region proposal network (RPN) in Faster R-CNN effectively learns the proposals on the COCO dataset, and the result in this submission is obtained by using only 300 proposals per image for a single model. The object detection network is built based on the observations in [d]. Both object detection and instance segmentation systems benefit greatly from the extremely deep residual networks. On the COCO detection dataset, Faster R-CNN with a 101-layer residual net shows 30% relative improvement over the counterpart Faster R-CNN with VGG-16. The training set for the classification network is the 1000-class ImageNet training set. The training set for the detection task is the MS COCO trainval set with box-level annotations. The training set for the segmentation task is the MS COCO trainval set with mask-level annotations. [a] “Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition”, Kaiming He, Xiangyu Zhang, Shaoqing Ren, Jian Sun. Tech Report 2015. [b] “Instance-aware semantic segmentation via multi-task network cascades”, Jifeng Dai, Kaiming He, Jian Sun. Tech Report 2015. [c] “Faster R-CNN: Towards Real-Time Object Detection with Region Proposal Networks”, Shaoqing Ren, Kaiming He, Ross Girshick, Jian Sun. NIPS 2015. [d] “Object Detection Networks on Convolutional Feature Maps”, Shaoqing Ren, Kaiming He, Ross Girshick, Xiangyu Zhang, Jian Sun. arXiv 2015.

description: We empirically investigate two complementary methods of improving object detection: (1) we incorporate global image context using stacked lateral recurrent neural networks with rectified linear units and (2) we use skip connections to pool from many different layers in the network and combine them with L2 normalization and re-scaling.  We use a single VGG16 ConvNet model based on Fast R-CNN, with a mix of proposal boxes from MCG (Multiscale Combinatorial Grouping) and RPN (Region Proposal Network, from Faster R-CNN).  We have no augmentation or ensembling at test time (single ConvNet, single scale, single crop, and no flipping).  The method will be posted to arXiv soon, and open source code will be released.  Runtime: ~2.7s per image on a Titan X GPU to evaluate 4000 candidate boxes (excluding proposal generation).

description: Our region based detector consists of the following components. 1) 300 box proposals generated by AttractioNet[1] which is a VGG16-Net based box proposal model pre-trained on ImageNet and fine-tuned on COCO 2014 train set. 2) A WRN-32[2] (Wide Residual Network) based detection model is applied on those proposals. It consists of two subnetworks. -- a Multi-Path[3] recognition module for the categorization of the box proposals and -- a LocNet InOut[4] localization module for category-specific object location refinement. It was pre-trained on ImageNet and fine-tuned on COCO 2014 train+val35 sets. 3) As post-processing we apply Non-Maximum-Suppression with Box Voting[5]. During test-time we use horizontal image flipping and four image scales (400, 600, 800, and 1000). We did not use model ensembles. description: We trained a large-batch object detector, MegDet, by Megvii (Face++)’s large-scale deep learning framework called MegBrain, in parallel, on 128 GPUs. Thanks to MegBrain, we were able to finish the whole training within ~1 day and got improved performance due to the large batch size. The design of our detectors follows the idea of FPN[1], whose feature extractors are a series of ReNeXt-like models pre-trained on ImageNet only. GCN modules[2] and instance-blind segmentation supervision[3] were also applied in the detector. We did not use the unlabeled images provided by MSCOCO or other training data. On the test-dev, our best single detector had obtained mAP 50.5, and the ensemble of four detectors had achieved mAP 52.6. [1] Tsung-Yi Lin, Poitr Dollár, Ross Girshick, et al. description: We used four models ensemble with the joint Soft-NMS [5], and each model are as follows:1) Three models of Deformable convolutional network using R-FCN architecture with ResNet-101 as backbone CNN [1,2,4] from different hyper parameters. 2) One model of Deformable convolutional network using Faster-RCNN architecture with ResNet-101 as backbone CNN [1,3,4]. We also apply semi-supervised learning (SSL) with coco unlabeled2017 dataset using pseudo labeled boxes extracted by deformable R-FCN which trained with train-val2017 dataset. To filter false label from the deformable R-FCN, we adopted prior knowledge from coco train-val2017 ground truth information as a co-occurrence matrix. The co-occurrence matrix represent that which objects appear together in a single image, and it will regulate soft-max output to prevent over-sampled boxes from unlabeled2017. And we assumed the conditional independence of each co-occurrence to filter false labeling for SSL. Unfortunately, we did't try multi-resolution testing to our models due to lack of time and resources. Additional remarks: - Detailed in best single model performance. Model: Deformable R-FCN with ResNet-101. Training resolution: [1200 800]. Test resolution: [1200 800]. Inference time: around 0.3~0.4s for forwarding. Training set: train2017 + val2017 + unlabeled2017 with pseudo label. Best performance: 38.7 for test-dev2017. These are main references for our submission: [1] Jifeng Dai et al., "Deformable Convolutional Networks", arXiv:1703.06211. [2] Jifeng Dai et al., "R-FCN: Object Detection via Region-based Fully Convolutional Networks", arXiv:1605.06409. [3] S. description: To improve the detection performance on coco, we made the following efforts: (a) We propose a novel proposal generation algorithm based on heat maps that can provide anchors in diversified shapes. The proposals produced by both original Region Proposal Network and our algorithm are adopted in this competition; (b) We introduce the use of both Faster R-CNN detection pipeline and Deformable R-FCN detection pipeline. The results of these two detection pipelines are ensembled for better mAP. We use multi-scale testing for both detectors. The best single model performance is 40.5 on test-dev. The speed is around 0.4~0.5s for one image (single scale); (c) We introduce a novel bounding box suppression algorithm in comparison to original NMS and soft-NMS algorithm; (d) No external data is used.

description: The entry is based on Deformable ConvNets [1] and Xception network [2]. The deformable convolution and deformable RoI pooling modules introduced in [1] can effectively enhance the transformation modeling capacity of ConvNets. The new modules can readily replace their plain counterparts in existing ConvNets and can be easily trained end-to-end by standard back-propagation, giving rise to Deformable ConvNets. On top of a strong baseline (Xception + FPN [3] + SoftNMS [4]), Deformable ConvNets boost the mAP by a clear margin (~3%). In the entry, ImageNet classification is the only external data utilized for network pretraining. The single model performance of Deformable ConvNets is 48.5% (with Xception + FPN + SoftNMS). The final entry utilize an ensemble of 6 models. [1] Jifeng Dai, Haozhi Qi, Yuwen Xiong, Yi Li, Guodong Zhang, Han Hu, Yichen Wei. "Deformable Convolutional Networks". In ICCV 2017. description: We submit three cases: (1) ConcatFPN: concatfpn-test.zip (SingleModle); (2) SE-CoupleNet: detections_test2017_se-couplenet_results.zip (Single Model); (3) DFM-SE-CoupleNet: detections_test2017_DFM_SE-CoupleNet_results.zip (Ensemble Model) We use only MS-COCO 2017 train data without any external data. (1) ConcatFPN It was trained following FPN [1] pipeline with ResNet101 as backbone. In our approach, we crop features from all levels instead of assign region proposal to single pyramid level. Obtained features are concatenated and passed through 1x1 convolution for complexity reducing. Such modification allows us to get +1.8 points in val2017. For final submission voting and multiscale testing were applied. Inference time is about 300ms on Tesla M40. (2) SE-CoupleNet It was trained following CoupleNet [2] pipeline with SE-ResNeXt-101 [3] as backbone. Compared with original ResNet-101 backbone, the performance is dramatically increased. Also, instead of ROI poolying layer, we use ROI Align [4] layer to fix the misalignment in pooling step. For final submission, soft-nms [5] and multiscale testing were applied. Inference time is about 270ms on Tesla M40. (3) Ensemble Model: This is a ensemble model. It combines three models as follows: - Deformable R-FCN (backbone: ResNet-101) with feature concatenation. Based on Deformable R-FCN, we add feature concatenation with three levels for classification. Inference time is about 400ms on Tesla M40. - Deformable CoupleNet (backbone: SE-ResNet-101) with ROI Align. We use SE-ResNet-101 [3] as backbone. In order to improve the performance, we add deformable convolutional layers and deformable roi pooling [6] in CoupleNet. Also, ROI Align [4] is used to fix the misalignment in pooling step. Inference time is about 300ms on Tesla M40. - CoupleNet (SE-ResNeXt-101) with ROI Align. This is same to (2) SE-CoupleNet. For final submission, soft-nms [5] and multiscale testing were applied. [1] FPN: "Feature Pyramid Networks for Object Detection", https://arxiv.org/abs/1612.03144 [2] CoupleNet: "CoupleNet: Coupling Global Structure with Local Parts for Object Detection", https://arxiv.org/abs/1708.02863 [3] SE-ResNet-101, SE-ResNeXt-101: "Squeeze-and-Excitation Networks", https://arxiv.org/abs/1709.01507 [4] ROI Align: "Mask R-CNN", https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06870 [5] soft-nms: "Improving Object Detection With One Line of Code", https://arxiv.org/abs/1704.04503 [6] Deformable: "Deformable Convolutional Networks", https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06211

description: We develop a novel region-based object detection and instance segmentation approach by boosting information flow from across layers, iterative pyramid and global context information. We use a feature pyramid Mask RCNN as our backbone [1, 2]. Our contributions are listed as follows. 1) Instead of assigning object proposals to different levels by a heuristic metric, we allow each proposal adaptively to pick useful information from all levels, leading to improved information flow from across layers. 2) We augment another path from lower layers to top layers based on the observation that larger objects could surprisingly benefit more from lower layer features, resulting in improved information flow from iterative pyramid. 3) We augment the FCN-like mask prediction branch with tiny fully-connected layers, improving information flow from global context information when predicting pixel-wise mask. As a result, masks with higher quality are produced. Our models are pre-trained on ImageNet and fine-tuned on COCO trainval subset with mask annotations. We directly take the tighten bounding boxes around each mask prediction as our object detection results. Our best single model performance is 44 in terms of instance segmentation and 47.8 in terms of object detection on test-dev subset. We find that the performances based on Resnext-101 (64*4d), SE-ResNext-101 (32*4d), Resnet-269 and SENet are just comparable. We hypothesis the reason is that the limited GPU memory makes the larger models can only be trained on smaller image input which limits their capability. For ensemble, we used 3 Resnext-101 (64*4d), 2 Se-ResNext-101 (32*4d), 1 Resnet-269 and 1 SENet. With network ensemble, we achieve 46.7 in terms of instance segmentation and 51 in terms of object detection on test-dev subset. [1] T. Lin, P. Dolla ́r, R. B. Girshick, K. He, B. Hariharan, and S. J. Belongie. Feature pyramid networks for object detection. CVPR 2017. [2] K. He, G. Gkioxari, P. Dolla ́r and R. B. Girshick. Mask R-CNN. ICCV 2017.

description: We propose a novel object detection network, named Context Pyramid Attention Network (CPANet). CPANet effectively integrates image context and spatial pyramid feature, and it is more accurate than the R-FCN baseline. In order to obtain higher accuracy, we train the Aligned Inception-ResNet101 on ImageNet-1k as our feature extractors, and then fine-tune it on the MSCOCO2017 trainval set.  This entry reports single model accuracy with multi-scale and horizontal flipping training. In test phase, we only adopt soft-nms without other bells and whistles (like multi-scale or multi-crop testing).
A PVANET trained on coco 2014 train/val and our own data.

description: We use 5x DeNet-101 models with the Joint Fitness NMS (unpublished) method. Models were trained at 512x512 and tested with 6x scales with the largest dimension resized to [384,512,768,1024,1280,1536]. A pretrained ImageNet ResNet-101 model is used as the base model. Method does not use RoI anchors / priors (reducing manual engineering), instead corner estimation and a Naive Bayes classifier is used for RoI estimation. RoI pooling is performed via Nearest Neighbour sampling on a spatially large top most feature map, providing improved evaluation rates. Multi scale, Single Model Performance: 42.3% MAP on test-challenge2017 Single Scale, Single Model Performance: 39.2% MAP @ 10 Hz on Titan X (Maxwell) on test-dev2017. ​Project URL: https://github.com/lachlants/denet Publication URL: https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.10295
